  "opinion": "As a woman in her seventies who’s worked as a cleaner in Bologna for decades, I’ve seen how science and technology often feel like a world away from the everyday struggles many of us face. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about the quiet, unspoken barriers that make it hard for women, especially those without formal education beyond lower secondary, to step into these fields. When I volunteer at the local community center, I hear stories from women like me who were told they weren’t ‘smart enough’ or ‘too emotional’ to pursue science. Back in my day, girls were expected to stay home and take care of the family, not go to university or work in labs. Even today, in a society that values both creativity and practical skills, the message still lingers: science is for boys. But should we address it? Absolutely. And how? By making science accessible without demanding formal education. In my neighborhood, I’ve seen young girls in rock climbing and cinema clubs who are naturally curious but don’t know where to start. We need to create safe spaces where they can explore science through hands-on activities, like building simple machines or observing nature. My own creativity has always led me to see the world differently—science isn’t just about formulas; it’s about asking questions and finding answers together. I believe the key is to start small, with community-based programs that honor the diversity of skills and backgrounds. If we want to close the gap, we must remember that science belongs to everyone, not just those who fit a narrow mold. It’s time to stop waiting for the ‘right’ person and start welcoming the ‘right’ questions.",
